                    </div>
                    <span>I have had this book for quite a few years and finally decided to read it.  I found that this book (often quoted in corporate america) was good but not the best book on strategy that I have ever read.  I believe that his writings were very well done and provided some good insight as to how to strategize and understand your enemies.  I believe that a solid person with good life experiences would understand many of these situations already.  There was some valuable information though and I can see how this information was conveyed into corporate culture.  </span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Small size - Impressive content </div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>8</span>
                      /
                      <span>8</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-04-07</span>
                    </div>
                    <span> 
<br />This edition of "The Art of War" (from Running Press) is indeed a small volume - a miniature book that will just about fit in a shirt pocket.  The contents, however, are quite impressive.  Sun Tzu's book is not only the earliest known treatise on warfare and  strategy, it is still considered to be quite profound and one of the most important ever written.
<br />
<br />If you would like a more hefty volume - a real book - you might want to consider getting "The Art of War by Sun Tzu - Special Edition" (ISBN 0976072696 ) which contains two separate versions of the Giles translation, one with and one without commentary and annotation.
<br />
<br />Regardless of which edition you get, you will be richly rewarded.  To share the thoughts and considerations of a genius, across a time span of two and a half millennia, is a rare privilege.  </span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">I liked it!</div>
