                    <span>Man, at first when I got the book I was like: damn this is a small book, but when I started reading it...I loved this book, it gets you thinking bout what he's talking about. </span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">But does it live up to the hype?</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>3</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>9</span>
                      /
                      <span>19</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-02-04</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>Well, I decided to check out Sun Tzu's art of war, since it's one of those books that you always find people discussing. Although I did not read this translation, but one that I found in a local bookshop, I was quite disappointed. The book gives you some understanding of the warfare of Sun Tzu's era, but I found the parts of it that can be applied to modern life are scant. What's more, what *can* be applied to contemporary life is all very obvious anyway. It can really be summed up in the following sentence: don't be stupid. So, for people looking to gain some valuable insight, it will probably be a disappointment. For those looking to discover something about the warfare of Sun Tzu's time, this will probably be a pretty good book to read.
<br />
<br />Like another reviewer mentioned: "Art of War's popularity outstrips its actual greatness."</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Compact but great.</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>17</span>
