                    </div>
                    <span>Both this and Machiavelli's "The Price" are small books but the knowledge in them are priceless.
<br />
<br />Sun Tzu has many great points the greatest being "if you do not know how to win, then you can not win."  Sun Tzu teaches you to think strategically, how to appraise your advisary, how to apparise the timing and locations of your perspective conflict, and how to appraise yourself.
<br />
<br />Sun Tzu is basically telling the reader that conflict can be broken down systematically and that once you learn how to read the conflict you can make decision were you gain the most and lose the least.
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />Now my beef with that yuppie who wrote "Sun Tzu is a sissy".  You sir are a Jackass, Sun Tzu says aviod conflict where you are going to lose, not to aviod all conflict.  Of course if you will gain in a conflict you should pursue it, but Sun Tzu does say perpetual conflict is unhealthy, which is true.  Perpetual conflict wears you down and eventually you will make a mistake and disappear in the long line of jackasses that never learned this.  Just because sucessful people in business are predatory does not mean Sun Tzu was wrong.  Those people that heavly invested in the Stock Market right after 9-11 were following Sun Tzu's advice, they seen their advisaries were weak(all the morons leaving), they seen the time was right(fatalistic the world is ending BS in the news), and they acted(got heavly invested in the market).  Shortly after that the market rebounded and now they are out with a healthy profit.
<br />
<br />Sun Tzu's systematic thinking is the cornerstone of good judgement, just because you read at a public school in Texas's sixth grade level does not mean Sun Tzu is wrong.  you are just  a bafoon tring to make a quick buck on a catchy name.  Ya jackass........</span>
                  
              
